"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 15–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-15-17.py

Historical/cultural/geographical context focus only.
NOT Greek lexical analysis (mkt-original) and NOT typology/Christology (mkt-christ).

Key context decisions for this range:
- Ch15 handwashing: oral Torah vs. written Torah, corban vow mechanics
- Canaanite woman: Tyre/Sidon region, Syro-Phoenician identity, "dogs" and ethnic
  boundary language in Jewish-Gentile interaction
- 4000 feeding: Decapolis territory, Gentile setting distinguishing from 5000 feeding
- Ch16 sign demand: Pharisee/Sadducee alliance, leaven as teaching metaphor
- Caesarea Philippi: northernmost point of Jesus' ministry, Herod Philip's capital,
  Pan sanctuary (Paneas), imperial cult dedication by Philip
- Peter's confession: "Son of the living God" vs. other messianic titles
- "Rock" (petra/petros): wordplay in Aramaic (Kepha), keys of the kingdom
  as rabbinic binding/loosing authority
- First Passion prediction: elders/chief priests/scribes = three Sanhedrin bodies
- Transfiguration: Mount Hermon setting, Moses/Elijah appearance, divine voice echoing baptism
- Elijah traditions, lunatic boy exorcism, Temple tax (didrachmon) mechanics
- v15:1, v16:21, v17:2 already present; merge_comm skips them
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: Historical/cultural/geographical context for Matthew 15-17; covers purity
#   controversies, the Caesarea Philippi confession, and the Transfiguration.
# CHANGE? If verse keys change in data/interlinear/matthew.json, update dict keys here.
# VERIFY: Run script; confirm ch15=39, ch16=28, ch17=27 verses in output.

MATTHEW = {
  "15": {
    "2": '<p>The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 complaint about the disciples not washing hands before eating refers to the oral Torah\xe2\x80\x99s extension of priestly purity requirements to all Israelites. Exodus 30:17-21 required priests to wash hands and feet before approaching the altar; the Pharisaic tradition extended this to laypeople before meals as an expression of Israel\xe2\x80\x99s "kingdom of priests" calling (Exod 19:6). This was not a hygiene practice but a ritual purity action, and it was oral tradition rather than written Torah — making Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 challenge in vv. 3-9 theologically precise.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"And why do you break the commandment of God for the sake of your tradition?" — the counter-charge employs the same verb (<em>parabainō</em> = transgress, break) the Pharisees used implicitly about the disciples. The inversion is rhetorically powerful: those who accuse others of transgression are themselves transgressing. The "commandment of God" (<em>entolēn tou theou</em>) is the written Torah, specifically the fifth commandment (Exod 20:12; Deut 5:16); the "tradition of men" is the oral halakha that has overridden it.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The fifth commandment — "Honor your father and your mother" (Exod 20:12) and "whoever reviles father or mother must surely die" (Exod 21:17) — was explicit written Torah with capital sanction. The combination of the positive command (honor = support financially) and the negative sanction (death for cursing parents) established the highest obligation of filial piety in Jewish law. Jesus cites both to establish the legal weight of the commandment before showing how tradition has nullified it.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The <em>corban</em> vow (<em>Dōron ho ean ex emou ōphelēthēs</em> = "Whatever you might have received from me is a gift [dedicated to God]") was a real halakhic device recorded in the Mishnah (m. Nedarim 9:1) by which a person could declare property as dedicated to the Temple, rendering it unavailable for other uses. The problematic application Jesus cites is using the corban formula specifically to avoid financial support of aging parents: by declaring your support-money as corban, you technically dedicated it to God and could not give it to your parents, yet you could retain use of it yourself. This allowed the letter of piety toward God to nullify the commandment of piety toward parents.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"You have made void the word of God for the sake of your tradition" (<em>ēkyrōsate ton logon tou theou dia tēn paradosin hymōn</em>) — the strong verb <em>akuroō</em> (to invalidate, deprive of authority) was a legal term for nullifying a contract or ruling. The charge is not that the tradition was wrong in itself but that the specific application of the corban rule nullified an explicit Torah commandment — a violation of the hermeneutical principle that oral tradition must serve written Torah, not override it.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The citation of Isaiah 29:13 — "This people honors me with their lips, but their heart is far from me; in vain do they worship me, teaching as doctrines the commandments of men" — places the Pharisaic tradition problem within the prophetic critique of empty formalism. Isaiah 29 addresses Jerusalem\'s leaders during the Assyrian crisis who performed the outward forms of worship while their inner orientation was distant from God. Jesus applies the same prophetic critique to the specific mechanism by which tradition has displaced Torah.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Isaiah\'s complaint "this people honors me with their lips, but their heart is far from me" was understood in Second Temple Judaism as an ongoing prophetic indictment with ongoing applicability. The citation is from the LXX version, which differs slightly from the MT. The "lips/heart" contrast activates the covenantal internalization language of Deuteronomy: true covenant faithfulness must be inscribed on the heart (Deut 6:6; 30:14), not merely performed on the lips. External compliance without internal alignment is the structural failure Isaiah diagnosed.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Teaching as doctrines the commandments of men" (<em>didaskontes didaskalias entalmata anthrōpōn</em>) — the elevation of human tradition to the status of divine commandment is the specific error. Mishnah tractate Avot (1:1) specifically instructed rabbis to "make a fence around the Torah" — to create additional protective regulations beyond the Torah\xe2\x80\x99s requirements to prevent accidental violation. The fence-building impulse was legitimate; its abuse was when the fence regulations began to be treated as Torah itself rather than as protective applications of Torah.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Hear and understand" (<em>akousate kai syniete</em>) calls the crowd back into the teaching circle after the private confrontation with the Pharisees. The move from insider conflict to public teaching is deliberate: the purity teaching that follows is addressed to everyone, not just the religious professionals. Jesus publicly challenges a defining feature of Pharisaic practice.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"It is not what goes into the mouth that defiles a person, but what comes out of the mouth; this defiles a person" — this principle challenged one of the foundational structures of Second Temple Jewish identity: the Levitical food purity system (Lev 11; Deut 14). The distinction between clean and unclean foods was a major marker of Jewish distinctiveness in the Greco-Roman world; observance of kashrut was one of the most visible signs of Jewish covenant identity. Mark 7:19 adds the editorial note "thus he declared all foods clean" — an implication the early church had to work through (Acts 10:9-16; Gal 2:11-14).</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Do you know that the Pharisees were offended (<em>eskandalisthēsan</em>) when they heard this saying?" — the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question about the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 offense reveals their concern about institutional relationships. The disciples were themselves Jews operating within the synagogue system and were aware of the social consequences of alienating Pharisaic leadership. The verb <em>skandalizō</em> (to offend, to cause to stumble) was used for the kind of offense that led to severance of relationship — the disciples recognized that Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching had created a serious social rupture.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Every plant that my heavenly Father has not planted will be rooted up" — the agricultural image of planting and uprooting was applied in Jewish literature to individuals and communities established by God versus those that were human constructions. The metaphor draws on Isaiah\xe2\x80\x99s vineyard imagery (Isa 5:1-7) and Jeremiah\xe2\x80\x99s planting imagery (Jer 1:10; 24:6). Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 dismissal of the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 offense as irrelevant — "let them alone; they are blind guides" — is a judgment that places the Pharisaic leadership outside the scope of God\xe2\x80\x99s eschatological planting.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"They are blind guides of the blind. And if the blind lead the blind, both will fall into a pit" — the blind-leader proverb draws on a social reality (blind persons navigating unfamiliar terrain) that was universally understood. In Jewish wisdom literature, the blind person was a figure for moral/spiritual ignorance rather than physical disability (Isa 29:9-10; 42:18-19; Zeph 1:17). The leader who cannot see cannot lead; those who follow sightless leaders share their fate. The Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 failure is not just personal but fatal for those they lead.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s request for explanation (<em>phrase</em> = interpret for us) treats the parable of inner defilement (v. 11) as a mashal requiring authoritative unpacking. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 incomprehension after the Beelzebul controversy (12:10) and the parable discourse (13:36) creates a pattern of misunderstanding that characterizes their learning: they hear but need private explanation. The request "explain the parable to us" mirrors the request at 13:36 ("explain to us the parable of the weeds").</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Are you also still without understanding?" — Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 expression of surprise at the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 incomprehension after all his teaching echoes the OT tradition of divine frustration with Israel\xe2\x80\x99s dullness (Isa 6:9-10; Jer 5:21; Ezek 12:2). The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 persistent incomprehension is not presented as stupidity but as a spiritual condition that the resurrection and Pentecost will ultimately transform. Their slowness of understanding serves the narrative purpose of requiring Jesus to explain clearly what his teaching means.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The physiology of digestion (<em>panta ta eisporeuomena eis to stoma eis tēn koilian chōrei kai eis aphedrōna ekballetai</em>) — the stomach receives food and the latrine evacuates it — grounds the purity teaching in observable bodily reality. Everything that enters the mouth passes through the body and exits; nothing ingested permanently contaminates the person\xe2\x80\x99s identity. This is a physiological argument against the ritual-purity logic of food prohibitions: the body itself does not retain the defilement of what it eats.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"But what comes out of the mouth proceeds from the heart, and this defiles a person" — the heart (<em>kardia</em>) in Hebrew/Jewish anthropology is the center of will, intention, and thought — not merely emotion. Prov 4:23 ("keep your heart with all vigilance, for from it flow the springs of life") is the Wisdom background; Jer 17:9 ("the heart is deceitful above all things") and Ezek 36:26 ("a new heart I will give you") establish the heart as the site of either covenant faithfulness or corruption. Defilement originates in the will, not in dietary contact.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The list of evils proceeding from the heart — evil thoughts, murder, adultery, sexual immorality, theft, false witness, slander (<em>ponēroi dialogismoi, phonoi, moicheiai, porneiai, klopai, pseudomartyiai, blasphēmiai</em>) — parallels the Decalogue sequence (sixth, seventh, eighth, ninth commandments) with an opening category of evil intentions. This suggests that the list is structured around the second table of the Decalogue (commandments governing human relationships), with "evil thoughts" as the intentional precondition for the specific violations. Sin begins in the will before it is enacted.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"These are what defile a person. But to eat with unwashed hands does not defile a person" — the conclusion directly answers the opening controversy (v. 2). The entire purity teaching — from the corban critique through the inner-defilement principle to the list of heart-evils — has been a single sustained argument that the Pharisaic handwashing tradition is both secondary (human tradition) and mislocated (targeting the wrong source of defilement). The conclusion restores the original charge and answers it definitively.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 withdrawal to the district of Tyre and Sidon (<em>anechōrēsen eis ta merē Tyrou kai Sidōnos</em>) moves the ministry into Phoenician coastal territory — modern Lebanon. This is the only time in Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s Gospel that Jesus leaves Israelite territory. Tyre and Sidon were prosperous Phoenician port cities with large mixed populations; the Syro-Phoenician (or Canaanite, as Matthew describes the woman) population was ethnically distinct from the Jewish population. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 presence in this territory is presented as withdrawal rather than mission to Gentiles — he came to be away from the controversy in Galilee.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The woman is identified as a "Canaanite" (<em>Chananaia</em>) — Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s archaic term activates the OT category of the paradigmatic enemy and other, the people Israel displaced in the conquest. Mark 7:26 uses the more contemporary "Syro-Phoenician." Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s "Canaanite" framing intensifies the ethnic-boundary transgression: this is not a neutral Gentile but a representative of Israel\xe2\x80\x99s ancient rivals. Her address — "Lord, Son of David, have mercy on me" — uses the Israelite messianic title, crossing the ethnic boundary in her terminology even as she crosses it physically by approaching Jesus.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"He did not answer her a word" — Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 silence is a social statement in a culture where acknowledged persons received acknowledgment. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 request — "send her away, for she is crying out after us" — was either a request to grant her petition (so she will stop following) or to dismiss her (so she will go away). The ambiguity in the Greek allows both readings; the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 concern is pragmatic management of a socially awkward situation rather than a theological position on Gentile mission.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"I was sent only to the lost sheep of the house of Israel" — the limitation of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 primary mission to Israel is consistent with the Mission Discourse (10:5-6: "Do not go among the Gentiles... go rather to the lost sheep of Israel"). In Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s theology, the Gentile mission is the post-resurrection commission (28:19: "make disciples of all nations"); the pre-resurrection mission is the covenant people\xe2\x80\x99s restoration. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 statement to the woman reflects this staged mission theology, making her persistence and faith all the more remarkable.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The woman\xe2\x80\x99s prostration (<em>prosekynei autō̄</em>) and simple petition "Lord, help me" (<em>Kyrie, boēthei moi</em>) is the most elemental form of supplication. In the ancient world, prostration before a powerful figure was the posture of absolute petition — one gave up any claim to standing or honor and threw oneself entirely on the other\xe2\x80\x99s mercy. The combination of prostration and minimal verbal request represents the complete absence of self-assertion.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"It is not right to take the children\xe2\x80\x99s bread and throw it to the dogs" — the "dogs" (<em>kynarion</em> = small dogs, household dogs) was a standard Jewish term of disparagement for Gentiles, reflecting the purity framework that associated Gentiles with uncleanliness. The diminutive form (<em>kynarion</em>) softens the insult slightly (household pet rather than street scavenger) but the ethnic boundary language remains sharp. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 use of the metaphor is pedagogical: he is testing whether her faith can navigate the boundary rather than asserting a personal conviction about Gentile worthlessness.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The woman\xe2\x80\x99s response — "Yes, Lord, yet even the dogs eat the crumbs that fall from their masters\xe2\x80\x99 table" — is a brilliant halakhic argument within the metaphor\xe2\x80\x99s framework. She does not deny the priority of the children (Israel) or claim equality with them; she accepts the metaphor and argues from within it that the dogs\xe2\x80\x99 inclusion does not require the children\xe2\x80\x99s exclusion. The household table produces enough for both. The argument is theologically precise: Gentile blessing is not the depletion of Jewish blessing but the overflow of it — a principle Paul will articulate in Romans 11.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"O woman, great is your faith!" — the exclamation marks this as a unique moment in Matthew: the only person praised for "great faith" by name (the centurion in 8:10 received the comparison "not even in Israel have I found such faith"). Her persistence, her theological creativity within the metaphor, and her willingness to accept a subsidiary position while still pressing her claim constitute the model of faith under apparent obstacle. The healing of her daughter at that moment ("from that moment her daughter was healed") is immediate and distance-based, paralleling the centurion\xe2\x80\x99s servant healing.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 return to the Sea of Galilee and ascent of a mountain (<em>anabas eis to oros ekathēto ekei</em>) near the Decapolis (implied by Mark 7:31\xe2\x80\x99s parallel: through the Decapolis) places this healing ministry in Gentile territory. The Decapolis was a league of ten (originally) Hellenistic cities east and southeast of the Sea of Galilee (Scythopolis, Gadara, Hippos, Pella, Philadelphia, and others) with predominantly Gentile populations and Greek cultural institutions. The mountain setting and the seated teaching posture echo the Sermon on the Mount geography but in Gentile territory.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The crowd bringing "the lame, the blind, the crippled, the mute, and many others" (<em>chōlous, typhlous, kullous, kōphous kai pollous heterous</em>) in Gentile territory creates a deliberate echo of the Galilean healing summaries (4:23-24; 9:35). The categories of healing match the messianic catalogue Jesus cited to John (11:5: blind see, lame walk, deaf hear) — now occurring among Gentiles. The crowd\xe2\x80\x99s glorification "of the God of Israel" (<em>edoxasan ton theon Israēl</em>) is unique: Gentile crowds praising Israel\xe2\x80\x99s God is an eschatological anticipation of the nations\xe2\x80\x99 inclusion (cf. Isa 2:2-4; 45:23; Zeph 3:9).</p>',
    "31": '<p>The phrase "they glorified the God of Israel" (<em>ton theon Israēl</em>) is significant precisely because Matthew uses it in a Gentile setting. The God of Israel is worshiped by non-Israelites on the basis of what they have witnessed — a fulfillment of the Isaianic vision of the nations recognizing YHWH through Israel\xe2\x80\x99s restoration (Isa 52:10; 66:18-21). The specific national designation "of Israel" underlines that the Gentiles are not worshiping a generic deity but the covenant God of a specific people.</p>',
    "32": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 compassion for the crowd in the wilderness after three days parallels the five-thousand feeding (14:14) but in a distinctly Gentile context. Three days in the wilderness without food would have been a significant physical stress; the detail grounds the miracle in an urgency that was not a test but a genuine welfare crisis. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question "where are we to get enough bread in such a desolate place (<em>erēmia</em>) to feed so great a crowd?" repeats the resource-inadequacy that preceded the five-thousand feeding, setting up the parallel miracle.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question — "Where are we to get enough bread in such a desolate place to feed so great a crowd?" — is often read as forgetful incomprehension after the five-thousand feeding. But the geography is different: they are in Gentile Decapolis territory, not in Bethsaida-adjacent Jewish territory. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question may reflect genuine uncertainty about whether the pattern of the five-thousand feeding would apply in Gentile territory — whether the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s abundance would extend to non-Israelites.</p>',
    "34": '<p>Seven loaves and a few small fish (<em>ichthydia oliga</em>) — the smaller starting inventory compared to the five loaves and two fish of the five-thousand feeding corresponds to the larger crowd and equally miraculous outcome. Seven as a number had cultural resonance in both Jewish and Gentile contexts; in rabbinic tradition, seven represented completeness. The seven baskets collected after the four-thousand feeding (<em>spyridas</em> = large rope baskets, distinct from the Jewish <em>kophinoi</em> of the five-thousand) may reflect Gentile cultural context through the different basket type.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The command to sit on the ground (<em>anapesein epi tēn gēn</em>) and the blessing, breaking, and distribution follow the same eucharistic pattern as the five-thousand feeding (14:19). The repeated structure links the two feedings as parallel events: the same pattern of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 provision for those who follow him operates in both Jewish (Bethsaida) and Gentile (Decapolis) settings. The early church reading these narratives would have recognized the sacramental form and the missional implication.</p>',
    "36": '<p>The giving of thanks (<em>eucharistēsas</em>) before breaking and distributing is the standard Jewish meal-blessing form (<em>birkat hamazon</em>) — now performed in Gentile territory for a Gentile crowd. This detail reinforces that the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s provision is not ethnically restricted: the same Jesus who blesses bread for five thousand Jews blesses bread for four thousand Gentiles using the same liturgical form.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Seven baskets of fragments gathered (<em>heptà spyridas plēreis tōn perisseumatōn</em>) — the seven baskets match the seven loaves, suggesting completeness of provision. The different basket word (<em>spyris</em> = large wicker basket, sometimes used for rope-made containers) from the five-thousand\xe2\x80\x99s <em>kophinos</em> (the distinctively Jewish wicker basket) appears in Acts 9:25 (the basket used to lower Paul from Damascus — a Gentile city). The basket distinction may be another marker of the Gentile context.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Four thousand men besides women and children — the crowd count is given the same formula as the five-thousand ("besides women and children"), using the same conventional census method of counting adult males. The four-thousand count in Gentile territory, smaller than the five-thousand in Jewish territory, may reflect the proportional distribution of population in each region or may simply be realistic narrative variation. The parallel structure of the two feedings (crowd + disciples + wilderness + inadequate food + miracle + surplus + count) is too deliberate to be accidental.</p>',
    "39": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 dismissal of the crowd and crossing to Magadan (or Magdala in some manuscripts) brings the ministry back to the Jewish western shore of the Sea of Galilee. Magdala (modern Migdal) was a prosperous fishing town and fish-processing center on the western shore, known in rabbinic literature as Tarichaeae. The return from Gentile Decapolis territory to Jewish Galilean territory completes the literary movement of the Tyre/Sidon and Decapolis section: Jesus briefly extended his ministry into Gentile regions before returning to the central arena of Galilean controversy.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>The Pharisees and Sadducees appear together — a politically remarkable alliance between theological opponents. The Pharisees believed in oral Torah, resurrection, and angels; the Sadducees accepted only written Torah and rejected resurrection. Their cooperation against Jesus reflects the principle that shared adversaries can unite otherwise incompatible groups. The demand for "a sign from heaven" (<em>sēmeion ek tou ouranou</em>) specified the celestial variety — publicly undeniable cosmic intervention — rather than the earthly healings and exorcisms Jesus had been performing.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The weather-reading analogy — "When it is evening, you say, \'It will be fair weather, for the sky is red\'" — draws on the universal agricultural practice of weather prognostication from sky colors. The red evening sky/fair weather and red morning sky/stormy weather pattern has a basis in atmospheric optics (particulate matter reflecting light) and was proverbially known across the ancient Mediterranean world. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 point is the irony of perceptive meteorological reading combined with theological blindness: the same observational skill that reads weather signs is absent when it comes to interpreting the signs of his ministry.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"You know how to interpret the appearance of the sky, but you cannot interpret the signs of the times" (<em>ta sēmeia tōn kairōn</em>) — <em>kairos</em> refers to the appointed time of opportunity or crisis rather than chronological time (<em>chronos</em>). The "signs of the times" are the same acts Jesus cited to John: blind see, lame walk, dead raised. The irony is pointed: weather signs are natural and observable; messianic signs are supernatural and even more observable, yet the religious experts miss them while peasant farmers read the sky.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign, and no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah" repeats the 12:39 response to an earlier sign demand. The repetition in a new geographic context (near Magadan rather than in the interior) and with a new coalition (Pharisees plus Sadducees) emphasizes the consistency of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 refusal: no institutional credential of the demanded type will be given. The departure (<em>katalipōn autous apēlthen</em>) enacts the refusal physically — Jesus simply leaves.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 forgetting to bring bread on the boat crossing is presented as an oversight that becomes the occasion for teaching. The boat journey across the Sea of Galilee from Magadan toward Bethsaida/Caesarea Philippi provides transition time. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 concern about bread supply — after two miraculous feedings — is presented as revealing a failure to appropriate what they had witnessed.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Watch and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees" — leaven as a metaphor for corrupting influence was natural in a culture where unleavened Passover bread was the annual symbol of purification from sin and Gentile contamination. Leaven spreads invisibly through dough and transforms the whole; a small amount corrupts a large batch. The Passover requirement to remove all leaven from the house (Exod 12:15) made leaven a powerful symbol for something that must be completely eliminated. Paul uses the same metaphor in 1 Cor 5:6-8.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 discussion among themselves about having brought no bread reflects their habitual tendency to interpret Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 sayings at the material rather than the symbolic level (cf. 15:15-16\xe2\x80\x99s request to explain the purity parable; John 4:32-33\xe2\x80\x99s misunderstanding about food). The gap between literal and symbolic reading is a consistent feature of the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 learning curve in all four Gospels, representing genuine pedagogical challenge rather than stupidity.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"O you of little faith, why are you discussing among yourselves the fact that you have no bread?" — the use of <em>oligopistoi</em> (little-faith ones) is Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s characteristic term for the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 partial, intermittent, and unstable faith (cf. 6:30; 8:26; 14:31; 17:20). The failure is not unbelief but the incapacity to hold onto what has been experienced and demonstrated. Two miraculous feedings are directly in view, making the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 bread-anxiety particularly pointed.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Do you not yet perceive? Do you not remember the five loaves for the five thousand, and how many baskets you gathered?" — the appeal to memory as the basis for present trust is a central Deuteronomic strategy: "remember what the Lord your God did" (Deut 7:18; 8:2; 16:3). The twelve baskets and seven baskets are cited as specific memorable details — the kind of precise numerical recall that should anchor trust. Memory of past provision is the antidote to present anxiety about supply.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The seven loaves and four thousand and the seven baskets gathered — the second feeding is cited alongside the first as double confirmation of the pattern. Two independent witnesses established a fact in both Jewish and Roman legal tradition (Deut 19:15; 2 Cor 13:1). Two miraculous feedings established a pattern: Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 presence with inadequate food resources + a crowd = miraculous provision with surplus. The disciples possessed two data points that should have made bread-supply anxiety impossible.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"How is it that you fail to understand that I did not speak about bread? Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees" — the rhetorical question circles back to make the teaching explicit: the warning was symbolic, not practical. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 literalism prevented them from receiving the metaphorical instruction. The identification of "leaven" with teaching (rather than moral corruption in Paul\xe2\x80\x99s usage) is Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 specific application: the Pharisees\xe2\x80\x99 and Sadducees\xe2\x80\x99 teaching is what spreads and corrupts.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Then they understood that he did not tell them to beware of the leaven of bread, but of the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees" — the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 comprehension completes the sequence: question, challenge, second question, comprehension. This is Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s characteristic learning-through-explanation pattern. The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 eventual understanding is noted despite their initial failure, maintaining their status as legitimate receivers of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Caesarea Philippi (<em>Kaisareia tēs Philippou</em>) was the northernmost point of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry — approximately 40 km north of the Sea of Galilee at the foot of Mount Hermon. The city was built by Herod Philip (son of Herod the Great) and dedicated to the emperor Caesar Augustus; Philip renamed the ancient city Paneas (modern Banias) as Caesarea in Augustus\xe2\x80\x99 honor, adding "Philippi" to distinguish it from Caesarea Maritima on the coast. A large grotto at the city contained the sanctuary of Pan (the Greek god of nature), and Herod the Great had built a white marble temple there dedicated to Augustus. This context — Gentile cultic sites, imperial temple, Pan sanctuary — frames Peter\xe2\x80\x99s Messianic confession as occurring in the most thoroughly pagan setting in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The people\xe2\x80\x99s identifications — John the Baptist, Elijah, Jeremiah, one of the prophets — reflect current Galilean opinion about Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 identity. Each category carried specific eschatological meaning: John the Baptist (14:2: Herod\xe2\x80\x99s superstitious identification, suggesting resurrected supernatural power); Elijah (the expected returning prophet before the Day of the LORD, Mal 4:5); Jeremiah (the weeping prophet of the destruction and exile, whose tradition included intercession for Israel, 2 Macc 15:14). Each identification correctly recognized Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 prophetic character without reaching the full messianic claim.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 direct question "But who do you say that I am?" (<em>hymeis de tina me legete einai</em>) shifts from public opinion to personal confession. The use of the emphatic "you" (<em>hymeis</em>) distinguishes the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 answer from the crowd\xe2\x80\x99s answer: they have had access to private instruction, explanations of parables, and eye-witness of miracles that the general crowd has not. Their answer is expected to be different because their information and relationship are different.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s confession "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God" combines two titles. "The Christ" (<em>ho Christos</em>) = the Anointed One (Hebrew: <em>Mashiach</em>), the expected Davidic deliverer-king. "The Son of the living God" adds a divine-relational dimension that exceeded standard Davidic messiah categories. The specific phrase "living God" (<em>tou theou tou zōntos</em>) was used in Jewish prayer and liturgy to distinguish Israel\xe2\x80\x99s God from the lifeless idols of the nations (Ps 42:2; 84:2; Jer 10:10; Dan 6:20) — a particularly pointed formulation in the context of the Pan sanctuary and imperial temple at Caesarea Philippi.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Blessed are you, Simon Bar-Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven" — "Bar-Jonah" (son of Jonah/John) is Peter\xe2\x80\x99s patronymic in Aramaic, the everyday language of Galilean Jews. The attribution of the confession to divine revelation rather than human reasoning grounds the Messianic recognition in the 11:27 claim: "no one knows the Son except the Father, and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him." Peter\xe2\x80\x99s confession is not a conclusion reached by analysis but a disclosure received by divine gift.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"You are Peter (<em>Petros</em>), and on this rock (<em>petra</em>) I will build my church" — the wordplay exists in Greek but was probably even clearer in Aramaic: Jesus would have said "You are Kepha (rock), and on this kepha I will build my community." The Aramaic <em>Kepha</em> (= rock) is preserved in 1 Cor 1:12; 3:22; Gal 1:18; 2:9. The "gates of Hades" (<em>pylai hadou</em>) as a cosmic force attacking the community draws on the ancient Near Eastern concept of the underworld\xe2\x80\x99s gates as the power of death and destruction. The promise that these gates will not prevail assures the community\xe2\x80\x99s indestructibility against the ultimate enemy.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven, and whatever you bind on earth shall be bound in heaven" — the "keys" imagery draws on Isa 22:22 (Eliakim given the key of the house of David) and represents authority to open and close access. The binding-loosing language (<em>deō/lyō</em>) was the standard rabbinic terminology for halakhic authority: a rabbi who "bound" ruled something prohibited; one who "loosed" ruled it permitted. The authority to bind and loose, given to Peter here and to the community in 18:18, is the authority to make halakhic and community-membership decisions whose divine ratification is guaranteed.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The command to "tell no one that he was the Christ" follows immediately after Peter\xe2\x80\x99s confession and the promise of keys — an apparently paradoxical silencing of the very truth just affirmed. The Messianic secret at this point reflects the same concern as earlier silencings: a premature public identification as Messiah would trigger political and military responses from the Herodian authorities and from popular messianic-military expectations. The disciples would only be free to proclaim the Messianic identity after the Resurrection had defined what kind of Messiah Jesus was.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s rebuke of Jesus — "Far be it from you, Lord! This shall never happen to you" (<em>Hileos soi, Kyrie; ou mē estai soi touto</em>) — uses the Greek <em>hileos</em> (= mercy! God forbid!) as a strong negative wish. Peter\xe2\x80\x99s objection reflects the fundamental incompatibility between the Davidic warrior-king messianic expectation and a messiah who suffers and dies. In every Second Temple messianic scenario, the Messiah was victorious and triumphant; a suffering messiah was a contradiction in terms. Peter is not being theologically obtuse — he is operating within the available categories.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Get behind me, Satan! You are a hindrance (<em>skandalon</em>) to me, for you are not setting your mind on the things of God, but on the things of men" — the term <em>skandalon</em> (stumbling block) echoes the beatitude of 11:6 ("blessed is the one who is not offended by me"). Peter, the rock on whom the church is built, immediately becomes a stumbling block when he opposes the Passion. The movement from "blessed are you" (v. 17) to "get behind me, Satan" (v. 23) in six verses illustrates the consistent NT theme that human-reasoning categories are inadequate for divine purposes.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me" — the cross-bearing language, coming immediately after the first Passion prediction and in the shadow of Roman power at Caesarea Philippi, was not metaphorical to first-century hearers. Roman crucifixion was a publicly visible form of execution; the image of carrying one\xe2\x80\x99s own crossbeam to execution was familiar in Palestine from Roman punitive practice. Jesus is not using "cross" as a metaphor for hardship; he is using the specific reality of Roman execution as a model for the orientation of discipleship.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"For whoever would save his life (<em>psychēn</em>) will lose it, but whoever loses his life for my sake will find it" — the paradox operates on the distinction between biological self-preservation and eschatological life. The <em>psychē</em> can mean biological life (what is preserved by avoiding danger) or the personal self/soul (what is found by giving up self-determination). The social context is the cost of public association with Jesus (v. 24: "take up his cross") — those who preserve their social standing by avoiding that association lose what matters; those who risk their standing find it.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"For what will it profit a man if he gains the whole world and forfeits his soul?" — the contrast of the whole world against a single soul employs the rhetorical form of hyperbole (gaining the entire world is the maximum possible acquisition) to make the point about value. The world\xe2\x80\x99s worth is finite and temporary; the <em>psychē</em> is the person in their covenantal identity before God. Jewish Wisdom literature consistently taught that material acquisition without righteousness was ultimately worthless (Prov 11:4; Eccl 2:1-11; Sir 11:18-19).</p>',
    "27": '<p>"For the Son of Man is going to come with his angels in the glory of his Father" — the Parousia language draws on Dan 7:13-14 (the Son of Man coming with the clouds, receiving dominion and glory) and Zech 14:5 (the LORD coming with all his holy ones). The promise of reward "according to what he has done" reflects the standard Jewish eschatological principle of judgment based on deeds (Prov 24:12; Ps 62:12; Jer 17:10; 2 Cor 5:10; Rev 20:12). The verse frames the cross-bearing call within the certainty of eschatological vindication.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, there are some standing here who will not taste death until they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom" — this verse has generated extensive interpretive debate. Options include: (1) the Transfiguration (vv. 1-8, which follows immediately); (2) the Resurrection; (3) Pentecost; (4) the destruction of Jerusalem in 70 CE as the Son of Man\xe2\x80\x99s coming in judgment; (5) the Parousia itself, implying imminent expectation. The immediate narrative placement of the Transfiguration (six days later, vv. 1-8) suggests Matthew intends a proleptic partial fulfillment in the Transfiguration, where the disciples "see" the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s glory.</p>'
  },
  "17": {
    "1": '<p>"After six days" (<em>meth\xe2\x80\x99 hēmeras hex</em>) — the six-day interval between the Caesarea Philippi confession and the Transfiguration echoes Exod 24:16: "The glory of the LORD dwelt on Mount Sinai, and the cloud covered it six days; on the seventh day he called to Moses from within the cloud." The Transfiguration is structurally framed as a Sinai theophany — a divine self-disclosure on a mountain, preceded by a waiting period. Peter, James, and John were the inner circle of the Twelve, the three witnesses of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 most intimate moments (cf. 26:37\xe2\x80\x99s Gethsemane).</p>',
    "3": '<p>Moses and Elijah (<em>Mōysēs kai Ēlias</em>) appearing with Jesus represented the two primary divisions of the OT as a whole — the Law (Moses) and the Prophets (Elijah as the paradigmatic prophet) — and also the two figures expected to appear at the eschaton. Malachi 4:4-5 ended the OT by invoking both "the teaching of my servant Moses" and "the prophet Elijah" who would come before the Day of the LORD. Their appearance together identifies the Transfiguration as an eschatological scene and places Jesus in continuity and climactic superiority to both.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Lord, it is good that we are here. If you wish, I will make three tents here, one for you and one for Moses and one for Elijah" — Peter\xe2\x80\x99s offer to build three <em>skēnas</em> (booths/tents) reflects the Feast of Tabernacles (<em>Sukkot</em>) framework. Sukkot was celebrated by building temporary booths (<em>sukkot</em>) in memory of the wilderness dwelling and in anticipation of the eschatological dwelling of God with his people (Zech 14:16-19; John 7:2 sets the first "I am" discourse near Sukkot). Peter instinctively reaches for the Sukkot-framework to interpret the theophanic dwelling-in-glory he is witnessing.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The bright cloud (<em>nephelē phōteinē</em>) overshadowing the disciples is the <em>shekinah</em> — the visible divine presence-cloud that appeared on Sinai (Exod 24:15-18), guided Israel in the wilderness (Exod 13:21-22), filled the Tabernacle (Exod 40:34-38), and filled Solomon\xe2\x80\x99s Temple at its dedication (1 Kgs 8:10-11). In Second Temple Judaism, the departure of the <em>shekinah</em> from the Temple (Ezek 10-11) was associated with the Babylonian exile; its eschatological return was eagerly anticipated. The voice from the cloud — "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased; listen to him" — echoes the baptismal voice (3:17) with the addition of "listen to him," activating Deut 18:15 (Moses\xe2\x80\x99 prophecy of the coming prophet: "to him you shall listen").</p>',
    "6": '<p>The disciples falling on their faces (<em>epesan epi prosōpon autōn kai ephobēthēsan sphodra</em>) is the standard OT theophany response: prostration before divine presence (Gen 17:3; Ezek 1:28; 43:3; Dan 8:17; 10:9). "Were terrified greatly" (<em>ephobēthēsan sphodra</em>) activates the sacred fear that distinguishes genuine theophany encounters from ordinary religious experience in the OT tradition. The disciples are not merely awed by a spectacular sight — they are responding to an actual encounter with divine presence.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"But Jesus came and touched them, saying, \'Rise, and have no fear\'" — the divine touch that resolves theophanic fear is a recurring pattern in Daniel (8:18; 10:10, 16, 18) where the figure who appears touches the fallen prophet and commands him to stand. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 action places him in the role of the divine comforter who lifts the prostrate from theophanic overwhelm. The command "have no fear" (<em>mē phobeisthe</em>) is the standard divine reassurance after theophany encounters (Gen 15:1; 26:24; Dan 10:12).</p>',
    "8": '<p>"And when they lifted up their eyes, they saw no one but Jesus only" (<em>Iēsoun monon</em>) — the disappearance of Moses and Elijah leaves Jesus as the single figure remaining. This is the Transfiguration\xe2\x80\x99s theological conclusion: the Law and the Prophets have been witnesses, but Jesus is the one. The voice\xe2\x80\x99s command "listen to him" (v. 5) is made visually concrete: Moses and Elijah are gone; only Jesus remains to be heard. The narrative enacts the "fulfillment" claim of 5:17 ("I have not come to abolish but to fulfill").</p>',
    "9": '<p>The command to "tell no one the vision until the Son of Man is raised from the dead" restricts the Transfiguration account to the post-Resurrection period. The Transfiguration as a vision (<em>to horama</em> = what was seen, a technical term for prophetic vision) would be incomprehensible without the Resurrection: a transfigured Jesus who was then crucified would produce misunderstanding about the nature of his mission. The Resurrection reframes the Transfiguration as a proleptic disclosure of resurrection glory rather than an escape from suffering.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Why do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?" — the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question connects the Transfiguration appearance of Elijah with the scribal tradition derived from Mal 4:5-6 (Elijah comes before the Day of the LORD). If Elijah has appeared at the Transfiguration, does this fulfill the scribal expectation? The disciples are trying to map the traditional eschatological sequence onto what they have just witnessed. The question reflects genuine theological puzzlement rather than doubt.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Elijah does come, and he will restore all things" — Jesus acknowledges the validity of the scribal interpretation of Malachi: Elijah\xe2\x80\x99s coming to "restore all things" (<em>apokatastēsei panta</em>) is legitimate eschatological expectation. The technical term <em>apokatastasis</em> (restoration, reconstitution) was used in Jewish apocalyptic for the eschatological restoration of Israel and the world to its proper order. Jesus affirms the expectation before reinterpreting its fulfillment.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"But I tell you that Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him, but did to him whatever they pleased. So also the Son of Man will suffer at their hands" — the identification of John the Baptist as the fulfillment of the Elijah expectation (cf. 11:14) is paired with the Passion prediction: John\xe2\x80\x99s treatment (imprisonment and beheading by Herod) anticipates Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 treatment. The "they did to him whatever they pleased" echoes the fate of the prophets in the deuteronomistic tradition (2 Chr 36:16; Jer 26:20-23; Neh 9:26): Israel consistently rejected and killed its prophets.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Then the disciples understood that he was speaking to them of John the Baptist" — the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 comprehension of the John-as-Elijah identification comes here, after the Transfiguration, whereas earlier (11:14) it required interpretive "willingness." The Transfiguration\xe2\x80\x99s disclosure of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 glory has apparently opened the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 capacity to understand the eschatological reframings Jesus has been offering.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The epileptic boy (<em>selēniazomenos</em> = moon-struck) represents the ancient medical/popular belief that certain conditions (convulsions, mental illness, epilepsy) were related to lunar cycles. The term "lunatic" in English derives from <em>luna</em> (moon) via this ancient tradition. Josephus (<em>Ant.</em> 8.2.5) describes Solomonic-tradition Jewish exorcism techniques; the attribution of convulsive conditions to demonic agency was the standard ancient etiology. The father\xe2\x80\x99s detailed description (falls into fire and water, frequent episodes) suggests genuine epilepsy or a severe convulsive disorder.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The father\xe2\x80\x99s approach with prostration (<em>gonypetōn auton</em> = kneeling before him) follows the same posture of petition seen throughout Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s healing narratives (8:2; 9:18; 15:25). The request "have mercy on my son" (<em>eleēson mou ton huion</em>) is the elemental petition form — mercy as the ground of appeal rather than merit. The detail that the disciples could not cure him creates the tension resolved by Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 exorcism-healing.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 failure to heal is presented without explanation at this point, building the tension that the private explanation in vv. 19-20 resolves. The failure is not attributed to lack of willingness or of authority — Jesus gave them authority over unclean spirits in 10:1 — but will be attributed to faith-inadequacy. The public failure of the disciples in front of a crowd was a social embarrassment that the private inquiry (v. 19: "came to Jesus privately") addressed.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"O faithless and twisted generation (<em>genea apistos kai diestrammenē</em>), how long am I to be with you?" — the address echoes Moses\xe2\x80\x99 exasperated lament in Deut 32:5 ("a crooked and twisted generation") and 32:20 ("for they are a perverse generation, children in whom is no faithfulness"). The wilderness generation\xe2\x80\x99s faithlessness provides the prophetic framework for the present generation\xe2\x80\x99s failure. The question "how long am I to be with you?" expresses the weariness of the divine patient presence with human recalcitrance, not personal frustration.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The exorcism by Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 command (<em>kai epetimēsen autō̄ ho Iēsous</em>) is immediate and complete, contrasting with the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 failure. The rebuke (<em>epitimaō</em>) is the standard exorcism command verb in the Synoptics (8:26; 17:18; Mark 1:25; 9:25; Luke 4:35). The boy\xe2\x80\x99s instantaneous healing ("and the boy was healed instantly") publicly restores what the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 failure had left broken, vindicating Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 authority while highlighting the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 limitation.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 private question "Why could we not cast it out?" reflects their awareness of the gap between their authority (given in 10:1) and their actual performance. The private inquiry (coming to Jesus "privately," <em>kat\xe2\x80\x99 idian</em>) is characteristic of the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 learning pattern in Matthew: public witness followed by private explanation. They are asking about methodology and capacity, not about whether the mission remains valid.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Because of your little faith (<em>di\xe2\x80\x99 oligopistian hymōn</em>)" — <em>oligopistia</em> (little faith) is Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s characteristic term for the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 condition (6:30; 8:26; 14:31; 16:8). The mustard seed comparison — "if you have faith like a grain of mustard seed, you will say to this mountain, \'Move from here to there,\' and it will move" — is a Jewish hyperbole for impossibly great action. The Talmud (b. Berakhot 64a; b. Sanhedrin 24a) uses "uprooter of mountains" as a title for exceptional sages; "nothing will be impossible for you" is the promise\xe2\x80\x99s scope, not a claim that physical mountains literally move on command.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Verse 21 — "But this kind never comes out except by prayer and fasting" — is absent from the best early manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and was likely added from Mark 9:29. This is a textual variant where the shorter reading is almost certainly original. The verse reflects the early church\xe2\x80\x99s practice of fasting before exorcism, which is attested in Didache 7:4 (fasting before baptism) and other early Christian sources. Its addition to Matthew by later scribes reflects the incorporation of fasting as a standard spiritual discipline into the apostolic commission narrative.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"As they were gathering in Galilee" — the second Passion prediction occurs during Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 continued Galilean ministry, before the final journey to Jerusalem (19:1). The geographical note situates the prediction at the heart of his earlier ministry region, creating a contrast between Galilee (where his ministry flourished among the people) and Jerusalem (where death awaited). The repetition of the Passion prediction (first at 16:21, now 17:22-23) reinforces its centrality and ensures the disciples have heard it before the events occur.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"They will kill him, and he will be raised on the third day (<em>tē̄ tritē̄ hēmera̧ egerthēsetai</em>)" — the passive voice "will be raised" (<em>egerthēsetai</em>) is the consistent NT form for resurrection: God raises Jesus rather than Jesus self-resurrecting. The "third day" formula derives from Hos 6:2 ("after two days he will revive us; on the third day he will raise us up") and may also reflect the Jewish belief that the soul hovered near the body for three days before final departure (m. Yebamoth 16:3). "They were greatly distressed" (<em>elypēthēsan sphodra</em>) — the disciples\xe2\x80\x99 grief is recorded despite or alongside their comprehension; hearing and receiving are different responses.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The Temple tax collection scene occurs in Capernaum — Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 home base. The two-drachma tax (<em>to didrachmon</em>) was the annual half-shekel contribution required of all adult male Jews for the Temple\xe2\x80\x99s maintenance (Exod 30:13-16; 38:26), equivalent to two days\xe2\x80\x99 wages. This tax was collected annually, typically in the month of Adar (February-March) before Passover, through collection booths set up throughout Jewish communities including the Diaspora. By Capernaum the tax-collectors were local Jewish agents of the Temple, not Roman tax farmers.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Peter\xe2\x80\x99s immediate "Yes" to the collectors and Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 preemptive question ("What do you think, Simon?") before Peter can report indicates Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 knowledge of the encounter. The analogy — "From whom do kings of the earth take toll or tax? From their sons or from others?" — employs common practice: rulers tax their subjects, not their own household. The "sons" who are exempt are the ruling family\xe2\x80\x99s members; the "others" are the taxed subjects. Applied to the Temple: if Jesus is the Son of the Temple\xe2\x80\x99s God, he is exempt from the Temple tax by the same logic.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Then the sons are free" (<em>eleutheroi ara eisin hoi huioi</em>) — the freedom of the king\xe2\x80\x99s children from tax is both the logical conclusion of the analogy and a statement about Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 identity. As the Son of the living God (16:16), Jesus is the "son" in relation to the Temple (the house of his Father); the Temple tax is paid to support the Father\xe2\x80\x99s house, but the Son of the house is not taxed to support his own Father\xe2\x80\x99s household. The exemption is theological, not a claim to civil immunity from taxation.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"However, not to give offense (<em>hina de mē skandalisōmen autous</em>)" — the decision to pay the tax despite the theological exemption is an application of the community principle: freedom exists but should not be exercised when it causes unnecessary stumbling in others. Paul applies the same principle in 1 Cor 8-9 (freedom to eat idol-meat, restricted by neighbor\xe2\x80\x99s conscience). The miracle of the coin in the fish\xe2\x80\x99s mouth provides the tax payment: a coin (<em>statēr</em>) worth exactly four drachmas = two didrachma taxes for two people (Jesus and Peter), paid miraculously from the sea that Jesus had just walked on and calmed.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew')
    merge_comm(existing, MATTHEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew', existing)
    print('Matthew 15-17 mkt-context written.')
    for ch in ['15', '16', '17']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
